<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,1086,2010]" box="[199,953,1230,1255]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1231,1255]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is a noun and refers to 
<typeStatus box="[808,856,1231,1255]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">type</typeStatus>
locality.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,1086,2010]" box="[199,698,1266,1291]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,476,1266,1291]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" reason="1">
Conditions of 
<typeStatus box="[367,472,1267,1291]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">holotype</typeStatus>
.
</emphasis>
Missing right leg I.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,1086,2010]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1302,1327]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The males of 
<taxonomicName authority="Cruz Da Silva &amp; Carico, 2012" authorityName="Cruz Da Silva &amp; Carico" authorityYear="2012" box="[483,614,1303,1326]" class="Phaeophyceae" family="Fucaceae" genus="Thaumasia" kingdom="Chromista" order="Fucales" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="species" species="caxiuana" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[483,614,1303,1326]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">T. caxiuana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[621,711,1303,1327]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[621,711,1303,1327]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
resemble those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mello-Leitao" authorityYear="1948" box="[925,1062,1302,1326]" class="Phaeophyceae" family="Fucaceae" genus="Thaumasia" kingdom="Chromista" order="Fucales" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="species" species="abrahami">
<emphasis box="[925,1062,1302,1326]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">T. abrahami</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1078,1160,1302,1326]" captionStart="FIGURES 84–87" captionStartId="49.[151,264,1932,1955]" captionTargetBox="[203,1390,185,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-71@49.[203,1390,185,1909]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURES 84–87. Thaumasia abrahami Mello-Leitão, 1948. Male palpus (84 ventral, 85 retrolateral, 86 detail of RTA, 87 detail of EcB). (C = conductor, DTP = distal tegular projection, E = embolus, EcB = ectal branch of RTA, EnB = ental branch of RTA, MA = median apophysis, RTA = retrolateral tibial apophysis, ST = subtegulum)." pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 84</figureCitation>
) by the rounded apex of the median apophysis, but can be distinguished by the shorter median apophysis (
<figureCitation box="[1070,1153,1338,1362]" captionStart="FIGURES 88–91" captionStartId="50.[151,263,1927,1950]" captionTargetBox="[204,1391,181,1906]" captionTargetId="figure-75@50.[204,1391,181,1906]" captionTargetPageId="50" captionText="FIGURES 88–91. Thaumasia caxiuana sp. nov. Male palpus (88 ventral, 89 detail of bulbus, 90 retrolateral, 91 detail of RTA). (C = conductor, DTP = distal tegular projection, E = embolus, EcB = ectal branch of RTA, EnB = ental branch of RTA, MA = median apophysis, RTA = retrolateral tibial apophysis, ST = subtegulum)." pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 89</figureCitation>
), by ental branch of RTA with a thin, lamellar base and a longer and slender tip (
<figureCitation box="[764,847,1374,1398]" captionStart="FIGURES 88–91" captionStartId="50.[151,263,1927,1950]" captionTargetBox="[204,1391,181,1906]" captionTargetId="figure-75@50.[204,1391,181,1906]" captionTargetPageId="50" captionText="FIGURES 88–91. Thaumasia caxiuana sp. nov. Male palpus (88 ventral, 89 detail of bulbus, 90 retrolateral, 91 detail of RTA). (C = conductor, DTP = distal tegular projection, E = embolus, EcB = ectal branch of RTA, EnB = ental branch of RTA, MA = median apophysis, RTA = retrolateral tibial apophysis, ST = subtegulum)." pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 91</figureCitation>
). The females resemble those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1898" box="[1212,1298,1374,1398]" class="Phaeophyceae" family="Fucaceae" genus="Thaumasia" kingdom="Chromista" order="Fucales" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="species" species="velox">
<emphasis box="[1212,1298,1374,1398]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">T. velox</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1313,1393,1374,1398]" captionStart="FIGURES 60–67" captionStartId="45.[151,263,1902,1925]" captionTargetBox="[172,1416,183,1888]" captionTargetId="figure-99@45.[172,1416,183,1888]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="FIGURES 60–67. Thaumasia velox Simon, 1898. Female epigynum (60 ventral, 61 dorsal, 62 detail of head of spermathecae), 63 trichobothria of right leg II, 64 position of tarsal organ (white arrow), 65 detail of tarsal organ, 66 tarsal claw of right leg I, 67 detail of inferior tarsal claw. (CD1 = copulatory duct 1, CD2 = copulatory duct 2, FD = fertilization duct, H = hood, HS = head of spermathecae, LL = lateral lobes, MF = middle field, P = pocket)." pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 60</figureCitation>
) by the presence of prominent lateral lobes and by the slightly projected middle field of epigynum (
<figureCitation box="[1217,1300,1410,1434]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–97" captionStartId="51.[151,263,1539,1562]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1513]" captionTargetId="figure-79@51.[151,1436,193,1513]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURES 92–97. Thaumasia caxiuana sp. nov. Female epigynum (92 ventral, 93 dorsal, 94 detail of the head of spermathecae), 95 trichobothria of metatarsi II, 96 detail of tarsal organ, 97 tarsal claw of right leg I. (CD1 = copulatory duct 1, CD2 = copulatory duct 2, FD = fertilization duct, H = hood, HS = head of spermathecae, P = pocket)." pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 92</figureCitation>
), but can be distinguished by the laterally less deeply excavated middle field (
<figureCitation box="[907,993,1446,1470]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–97" captionStartId="51.[151,263,1539,1562]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1513]" captionTargetId="figure-79@51.[151,1436,193,1513]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURES 92–97. Thaumasia caxiuana sp. nov. Female epigynum (92 ventral, 93 dorsal, 94 detail of the head of spermathecae), 95 trichobothria of metatarsi II, 96 detail of tarsal organ, 97 tarsal claw of right leg I. (CD1 = copulatory duct 1, CD2 = copulatory duct 2, FD = fertilization duct, H = hood, HS = head of spermathecae, P = pocket)." pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 92</figureCitation>
), by the shorter and folded copulatory ducts (
<figureCitation box="[225,306,1482,1506]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–97" captionStartId="51.[151,263,1539,1562]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1513]" captionTargetId="figure-79@51.[151,1436,193,1513]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURES 92–97. Thaumasia caxiuana sp. nov. Female epigynum (92 ventral, 93 dorsal, 94 detail of the head of spermathecae), 95 trichobothria of metatarsi II, 96 detail of tarsal organ, 97 tarsal claw of right leg I. (CD1 = copulatory duct 1, CD2 = copulatory duct 2, FD = fertilization duct, H = hood, HS = head of spermathecae, P = pocket)." pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 93</figureCitation>
) and by the shape of the head of spermathecae (
<figureCitation box="[846,930,1482,1506]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–97" captionStartId="51.[151,263,1539,1562]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1513]" captionTargetId="figure-79@51.[151,1436,193,1513]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURES 92–97. Thaumasia caxiuana sp. nov. Female epigynum (92 ventral, 93 dorsal, 94 detail of the head of spermathecae), 95 trichobothria of metatarsi II, 96 detail of tarsal organ, 97 tarsal claw of right leg I. (CD1 = copulatory duct 1, CD2 = copulatory duct 2, FD = fertilization duct, H = hood, HS = head of spermathecae, P = pocket)." pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 94</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="19" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,1086,2010]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,344,1518,1543]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" reason="1">Description.</emphasis>
Male (
<typeStatus box="[425,534,1518,1542]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Holotype</typeStatus>
, Melgaço, Pará, 
<collectingCountry box="[725,796,1518,1542]" name="Brazil" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, MPEG 15599). Total length 12.36. Carapace 6.38 long, 5.71 wide, light brown with a thin lateral white band. Clypeus light brown, 0.76 high. Anterior eye row slightly procurved (
<figureCitation box="[282,367,1590,1614]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–17" captionStartId="36.[151,263,1968,1991]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1942]" captionTargetId="figure-69@36.[151,1436,181,1942]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURES 10–17. Males of Thaumasia Perty, 1833, frontal view of chelicerae (10 T. annulipes, 11 T.velox, 12 T. caxiuana sp. nov., 13 T. argenteonotata, 14 T. abrahami, 15 T. onca sp. nov., 16 T. scoparia, 17 T. lisei sp. nov.)." pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
), 1.16 wide; posterior recurved, 2.10 wide. Eye diameters, interdistances, and median ocular quadrangle: AME 0.22, ALE 0.16, PME 0.32, PLE 0.40; AME-AME 0.20, AME-ALE 0.12, PME-PME 0.36, PME-PLE 0.44, OQA 0.66, OQP 1.00, OQH 0.70. Chelicerae light brown, slightly depressed laterally, without the tufts of white bristles laterally, with scattered bristles (
<figureCitation box="[789,876,1698,1722]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–17" captionStartId="36.[151,263,1968,1991]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1942]" captionTargetId="figure-69@36.[151,1436,181,1942]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURES 10–17. Males of Thaumasia Perty, 1833, frontal view of chelicerae (10 T. annulipes, 11 T.velox, 12 T. caxiuana sp. nov., 13 T. argenteonotata, 14 T. abrahami, 15 T. onca sp. nov., 16 T. scoparia, 17 T. lisei sp. nov.)." pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). Sternum yellow, bristly; 2.57 long, 2.90 wide. Labium light brown, dark brown laterally, 0.85 long, 0.99 wide. Legs light brown, unmarked, with numerous dark brown macrosetae; relative length: IV-I-II-III, I—femur 9.97/ patella-tibia 13.83/ metatarsus 8.24/ tarsus 3.85/ total 35.89; II—10.24/ 13.69/ 8.51/ 3.44/ 35.88; III—8.91/ 11.97/ 7.58/ 3.59/ 32.05; IV—10.37/ 13.96/ 9.70/ 4.52/ 38.55. Ventral pairs of macrosetae on tibiae: I-4; II-5; III-4; IV-4. Abdomen 5.85 long, dark gray with two parallel white bands formed by small white bristles; with two pairs of sigillae and two pairs of irregular white spots near the spinnerets. Venter light gray; with scattered bristles. Palpus with a conspicuous median apophysis, with a blunt apex (
<figureCitation box="[220,354,1950,1974]" captionStart="FIGURES 88–91" captionStartId="50.[151,263,1927,1950]" captionTargetBox="[204,1391,181,1906]" captionTargetId="figure-75@50.[204,1391,181,1906]" captionTargetPageId="50" captionText="FIGURES 88–91. Thaumasia caxiuana sp. nov. Male palpus (88 ventral, 89 detail of bulbus, 90 retrolateral, 91 detail of RTA). (C = conductor, DTP = distal tegular projection, E = embolus, EcB = ectal branch of RTA, EnB = ental branch of RTA, MA = median apophysis, RTA = retrolateral tibial apophysis, ST = subtegulum)." pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Figs 88, 89</figureCitation>
). Ental branch of RTA with a thin and short lamellar projection at the base (
<figureCitation box="[1233,1316,1950,1974]" captionStart="FIGURES 88–91" captionStartId="50.[151,263,1927,1950]" captionTargetBox="[204,1391,181,1906]" captionTargetId="figure-75@50.[204,1391,181,1906]" captionTargetPageId="50" captionText="FIGURES 88–91. Thaumasia caxiuana sp. nov. Male palpus (88 ventral, 89 detail of bulbus, 90 retrolateral, 91 detail of RTA). (C = conductor, DTP = distal tegular projection, E = embolus, EcB = ectal branch of RTA, EnB = ental branch of RTA, MA = median apophysis, RTA = retrolateral tibial apophysis, ST = subtegulum)." pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 91</figureCitation>
) and ectal branch of RTA short and with a rounded apex (
<figureCitation box="[676,806,1986,2010]" captionStart="FIGURES 88–91" captionStartId="50.[151,263,1927,1950]" captionTargetBox="[204,1391,181,1906]" captionTargetId="figure-75@50.[204,1391,181,1906]" captionTargetPageId="50" captionText="FIGURES 88–91. Thaumasia caxiuana sp. nov. Male palpus (88 ventral, 89 detail of bulbus, 90 retrolateral, 91 detail of RTA). (C = conductor, DTP = distal tegular projection, E = embolus, EcB = ectal branch of RTA, EnB = ental branch of RTA, MA = median apophysis, RTA = retrolateral tibial apophysis, ST = subtegulum)." pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Figs 90, 91</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,151,680]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Female (
<typeStatus box="[296,398,151,175]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Paratype</typeStatus>
, Melgaço, Pará, 
<collectingCountry box="[585,656,151,175]" name="Brazil" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, MCTP 33350). Total length 12.90. Carapace, colour as in male, 6.11 long, 5.45 wide, as in male. Clypeus light brown, 0.68 high. Anterior eye row slightly procurved, 1.18 wide; posterior recurved, 2.00 wide. Eye diameters, interdistances, and median ocular quadrangle: AME 0.22, ALE 0.20, PME 0.30, PLE 0.28; AME-AME 0.24, AME-ALE 0.14, PME-PME 0.38, PME-PLE 0.46, OQA 0.64, OQP 1.00, OQH 0.74. Chelicerae light brown. Sternum yellow, 2.90 long, 2.90 wide. Labium, colour as in male, 0.99 long, 0.91 wide. Legs yellow, unmarked; relative length: IV-II-I-III, I—femur 8.51/ patella-tibia 11.70/ metatarsus 6.91/ tarsus 3.32/ total 30.44; II—8.64/ 11.57/ 7.31/ 3.58/ 31.10; III—7.71/ 10.10/ 6.38/ 3.09/ 27.28; IV—8.63/ 11.83/ 8.11/ 4.25/ 32.82. Ventral pairs of macrosetae on tibiae: I-4; II-4; III-4; IV-5. Trichobothrial hood smooth and with two lateral projections (
<figureCitation box="[421,505,439,463]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–97" captionStartId="51.[151,263,1539,1562]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1513]" captionTargetId="figure-79@51.[151,1436,193,1513]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURES 92–97. Thaumasia caxiuana sp. nov. Female epigynum (92 ventral, 93 dorsal, 94 detail of the head of spermathecae), 95 trichobothria of metatarsi II, 96 detail of tarsal organ, 97 tarsal claw of right leg I. (CD1 = copulatory duct 1, CD2 = copulatory duct 2, FD = fertilization duct, H = hood, HS = head of spermathecae, P = pocket)." pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 95</figureCitation>
). Tarsal organ with an elliptical opening (
<figureCitation box="[980,1066,439,463]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–97" captionStartId="51.[151,263,1539,1562]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1513]" captionTargetId="figure-79@51.[151,1436,193,1513]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURES 92–97. Thaumasia caxiuana sp. nov. Female epigynum (92 ventral, 93 dorsal, 94 detail of the head of spermathecae), 95 trichobothria of metatarsi II, 96 detail of tarsal organ, 97 tarsal claw of right leg I. (CD1 = copulatory duct 1, CD2 = copulatory duct 2, FD = fertilization duct, H = hood, HS = head of spermathecae, P = pocket)." pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 96</figureCitation>
). Superior tarsal claw with eight teeth; inferior with one tooth (
<figureCitation box="[487,570,476,500]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–97" captionStartId="51.[151,263,1539,1562]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1513]" captionTargetId="figure-79@51.[151,1436,193,1513]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURES 92–97. Thaumasia caxiuana sp. nov. Female epigynum (92 ventral, 93 dorsal, 94 detail of the head of spermathecae), 95 trichobothria of metatarsi II, 96 detail of tarsal organ, 97 tarsal claw of right leg I. (CD1 = copulatory duct 1, CD2 = copulatory duct 2, FD = fertilization duct, H = hood, HS = head of spermathecae, P = pocket)." pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 97</figureCitation>
). Abdomen 7.31 long, colour as in male. Epigynum with a slightly excavated middle field and with conspicuous and deeply excavated hood (
<figureCitation box="[898,986,511,535]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–97" captionStartId="51.[151,263,1539,1562]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1513]" captionTargetId="figure-79@51.[151,1436,193,1513]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURES 92–97. Thaumasia caxiuana sp. nov. Female epigynum (92 ventral, 93 dorsal, 94 detail of the head of spermathecae), 95 trichobothria of metatarsi II, 96 detail of tarsal organ, 97 tarsal claw of right leg I. (CD1 = copulatory duct 1, CD2 = copulatory duct 2, FD = fertilization duct, H = hood, HS = head of spermathecae, P = pocket)." pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 92</figureCitation>
). Copulatory ducts elongated and wide (
<figureCitation box="[159,243,548,572]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–97" captionStartId="51.[151,263,1539,1562]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1513]" captionTargetId="figure-79@51.[151,1436,193,1513]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURES 92–97. Thaumasia caxiuana sp. nov. Female epigynum (92 ventral, 93 dorsal, 94 detail of the head of spermathecae), 95 trichobothria of metatarsi II, 96 detail of tarsal organ, 97 tarsal claw of right leg I. (CD1 = copulatory duct 1, CD2 = copulatory duct 2, FD = fertilization duct, H = hood, HS = head of spermathecae, P = pocket)." pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 93</figureCitation>
); head of spermathecae small and with pores (
<figureCitation box="[761,845,548,572]" captionStart="FIGURES 92–97" captionStartId="51.[151,263,1539,1562]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1513]" captionTargetId="figure-79@51.[151,1436,193,1513]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURES 92–97. Thaumasia caxiuana sp. nov. Female epigynum (92 ventral, 93 dorsal, 94 detail of the head of spermathecae), 95 trichobothria of metatarsi II, 96 detail of tarsal organ, 97 tarsal claw of right leg I. (CD1 = copulatory duct 1, CD2 = copulatory duct 2, FD = fertilization duct, H = hood, HS = head of spermathecae, P = pocket)." pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 94</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
